Subject: [PATCH 32/35] web-app: export a chat as a zip (html viewer + txt +
 json + media) from the three-dot menu
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Telegram-style chat export: an 'Export Chat' entry in the main-view
three-dot menu downloads the open chat as one zip containing

- index.html — a standalone viewer that renders the chat exactly like
  the desktop message list. Fidelity comes from reusing the app's own
  presentation: main.css/bundle.css/fallback-theme.css are embedded
  (css url() assets inlined as data: URIs; deliberately no theme vars —
  exports use the default theme) and the viewer emits the same DOM the
  message list renders (message bubbles, author/avatar, quotes,
  attachments, metadata footer, reactions, day markers). The message
  data is embedded as JSON and rendered by a small self-contained
  script (shipped via Function.toString of chatExportViewer), so the
  html also works when the json sits next to it. A
  'Save single-file HTML' button snapshots the rendered DOM with media
  inlined as data: URIs (or via webxdc.sendToChat when running as a
  webxdc app).
- messages.json — the raw jsonrpc data (chat, message-list items,
  getMessages results, media file map): groundwork for doing this
  export in core later.
- messages.txt — a plain-text transcript.
- media/ — attachments, avatars and quote images (50 MB per file /
  300 MB total budget; larger files render as the generic file tile).
- manifest.toml + icon — rename the zip to .xdc and it becomes a
  webxdc viewer app that can be sent into a chat.

The zip is assembled in the frontend (minimal store-only writer, the
bulk of the payload is already-compressed media), staged via
writeTempFileFromBase64 and handed to the user through
runtime.downloadFile; a progress dialog with cancel covers big chats.
Message text is escaped + linkified (no message-parser markdown, no
jumbomoji). New strings live in _untranslated_en.json.
